4 CONC l America&amp;lt;br&amp;gt;There seems to be an issue with this person&#039;s relatives. View this person on FamilySearch to see this information.&amp;lt;br&amp;gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Additional infor
4 CONC mation: &lt;br&gt; &lt;br&gt;CALENDARYEARSOFCOLONIALMASSACHUSETTSA: NOTE: In the Colonial days of Massachusetts, they ACCOUNTED their CALENDAR YEARS FROM THE END OF MARCH TO MARCH; Whereas the &quot;N
4 CONC ORMAL&quot; ACCOUNTING of a year for other Colonial States was from JANUARY TO JANUARY (same as we have today).  This different accounting of Massachusetts&#039; calendar year was to remind them that 
4 CONC at the &quot;new year&quot; it was time for them to plant their crops.  Thus, is the confusion that people may have, concerning some records that have double years, or when you see records that don&#0
4 CONC 39;t seem to make sense, example:  you may find a record of marriage intentions published in December 1737 and then a record of marriage showing the marriage took place in January of 1737.  that appea
4 CONC rs to be mismatched and incorrect.  But,  if you REMEMBER that COLONIAL MASSACHUSETTS&#039; YEARS WERE ACCOUNTED FROM THE END OF MARCH TO MARCH, it does make sense.  Thus, a  marriage year for January
4 CONC  1737, is correct, and in order,  if you go from December 1737 to January 1737 (to February 1737, to March 1737, to April 1738 -  because &quot;their&quot; new year would have started the end of march
4 CONC ).  Most of the time, the records will show DOUBLE YEARS, such as 1737/38 or 1737-38.  In this way, it tells you that ACCORDING TO MASSACHUSETTS, THE YEAR IS STILL 1737; but according to THE &quot;STA
4 CONC NDARD&quot; ACCOUNTING of a year, it is ACTUALLY 1738.  You will only find these &quot;DOUBLE YEARS&quot; recorded in the months of JANUARY THROUGH MARCH.  (Caps for emphasis).
