4 CONC Sketch: William Haskell married Mary Brown daughter of William Brown and Mary ____ on 3 Jul 1667 in Gloucester, Essex, Massachusetts. Mary was born on 28 Jul 1649 in Gloucester, Essex, Massachusetts. 
4 CONC She died on 12 Nov 1715 in Gloucester, Essex, Massachusetts.

Mary Brown was her birth name. She changed her surname to Walker after the marriage of her mother to Henry Walker, her mother&#039;s third
4 CONC  marriage. She is referred to in genealogical writings and records as either Mary Walker, Mary Brown, Mary Brown-Walker, or Mary Walker/Brown.

They had the following children:
1.) Mary Haskell was bo
4 CONC rn on 29 Apr 1668. She died on 1 Nov 1721.

2.) Ensign William Haskell was born on 6 Nov 1670. He died on 17 Jan 1731.

3.) Joseph Haskell was born on 21 Apr 1673. He died on 11 Apr 1718.

4.) Abigail
4 CONC  Haskell was born on 2 Mar 1676. She died on 5 May 1762.

5.) Henry Haskell was born on 2 Apr 1678. He died on 17 Apr 1739.

6.) Andrew Haskell was born on 27 Jul 1680 in Gloucester, Essex, Massachuse
4 CONC tts. He died on 14 Aug 1680 in Gloucester, Essex, Massachusetts.

7.) Lydia Haskell was born on 4 Sep 1681. She died on 2 Oct 1734.

8.) Sarah Haskell was born on 26 Feb 1683 in Gloucester, Essex, Mas
4 CONC sachusetts. She died on 20 Feb 1690 in Gloucester, Essex, Massachusetts.

9.) Elizabeth Haskell was born on 5 Apr 1686.

10.) Hannah Haskell was born 3, 4 on 30 Oct 1688 in Gloucester, Essex, Massachu
4 CONC setts. She died on 15 Feb 1690 in Gloucester, Essex, Massachusetts.

11.) Jacob Haskell was born on 15 Jan 1690. He died on 6 Aug 1757.

12.) Sarah Haskell was born on 11 Sep 1692. She died on 10 Jul 
4 CONC 1773.


William Haskell 1644-1708 owned a large grist mill and a saw mill in what is now Rockport, MA. The mills went eventually to his son, William 1670-1730/31, who continued to operate them. In May
4 CONC  1690, he and his brother Mark received permission and erected a saw mill on Walker&#039;s Creek. (From &quot;Chronicles of the Haskell Family&quot; by Ira J. Haskell, published by Ellis Ptinting Co.,
4 CONC  Lynn, MA.)

William&#039;s birth is recorded in the Vital Records of Gloucester, Massachusetts, v1, p330, but he was born on land (&quot;Planter&#039;s Neck&quot;) that is now part of the town of Ann
4 CONC isquam, MA. REF: &quot;Haskell Journal, Journal of the Haskell Family Association&quot;, v9, #2, 1993.

William Jr. was a fisherman as well as a farmer. He owned a fishing fleet in 1670 and later was 
4 CONC a member of the crew of the sloop Swan under Master Edward Winslow. He also owned a half interest in a grist and saw mill on Walker&#039;s Creek in West Gloucester with his brother Mark.

He was on th
4 CONC e Jury of Trials 18 May 1670, and 12 May and 24 June 1679. William was made Freeman at a General Court at Boston on 15 October 1684 and took the oath of Freeman at the court in Salem on 25 November in
4 CONC  the same year.

On 27 February 1688, along with other citizens of Gloucester, he was granted a six acre lot west of the cut in West Gloucester, Lot number twelve.

In addition to other land he inheri
4 CONC ted from his father, he also received a slip or point of marsh lying between the bridge of his mill creek and Mr. Wise&#039;s farm.

William Haskell Jr. died intestate, his inventory dated 12 July 170
4 CONC 8 was taken by Nathaniel Coit, Benjamin Marskott, and Isaac Eveleth.

It totaled £ 666:06:03, of which £ 503:03:00 was real estate. Articles of Agreement and Division of his property among his nine 
4 CONC children and/or their guardians was dated 7 July 1708.

His sons William, Joseph, Henry, and Jacob all received real estate, while his daughters, Mary Davis, Abigail Parsons, Lydia Parsons, Elizabeth 
4 CONC and Sarah Haskell each received £57:13:4.

William&#039;s widow Mary relinquished her dower rights 12 July 1708 in exchange for two hundred pounds and a yearly allowance. This release was witnessed b
4 CONC y John Newman, William Whittredge, and Thomas Andrus.
